const a="Ashwatthama",e=[{title:"Birth and Blessing",content:"Ashwatthama was born to Drona and Kripi, blessed with a gem on his forehead that gave him power over hunger, thirst, and fatigue. He was considered one of the Chiranjivis (immortals) destined to live until the end of time."},{title:"Training Under Drona",content:"As the son of Guru Drona, Ashwatthama received exceptional training in martial arts, archery, and the use of celestial weapons. He grew up close to the Kauravas and naturally sided with them."},{title:"Role in the Kurukshetra War",content:"Ashwatthama fought fiercely for the Kauravas, using his unmatched skills in warfare. He displayed bravery against many Pandava warriors and became a formidable opponent on the battlefield."},{title:"Death of Drona",content:"When Drona was deceitfully informed by Yudhishthira that his son was dead, he laid down his arms and was slain by Dhrishtadyumna. Ashwatthama was devastated by his father’s death and burned with vengeance."},{title:"Night Massacre",content:"In retaliation for Drona’s death, Ashwatthama launched a night attack on the Pandava camp. He killed Dhrishtadyumna, Shikhandi, and many others while they slept, an act considered against the rules of warfare."},{title:"Slaying of the Upapandavas",content:"In a tragic mistake or ruthless act of revenge, Ashwatthama killed the five sons of Draupadi, mistaking them for the Pandavas. This heinous act earned Draupadi’s eternal curse."},{title:"Use of the Brahmastra",content:"In desperation, Ashwatthama unleashed the Brahmastra against the Pandavas. Arjuna countered it with his own, and the clash threatened to destroy the world. Under Vyasa’s intervention, Arjuna recalled his weapon, but Ashwatthama, unable to do so, diverted it to strike the unborn child of Abhimanyu in Uttara’s womb."},{title:"Curse and Immortality",content:"For his heinous deeds, Krishna cursed Ashwatthama to live forever, wandering the earth with festering wounds and suffering loneliness, dishonor, and pain until the end of time."},{title:"Legacy",content:"Ashwatthama remains a tragic figure—one of the most skilled warriors of the Mahabharata, yet doomed by his own choices. His immortality makes him a haunting reminder of the consequences of unchecked vengeance."}],t={name:a,fullBiography:e};export{t as default,e as fullBiography,a as name};
